byline.original: By HAROLD M. SCHMECK Jr. Special to The New York Times

docs.lead_paragraph: AFTER years in the wilderness, Paul Goodman has recently emerged as a major prophet. The emergence coincides with the rebirth of radicalism among the college-age population, for it is the New Left that has conferred on Goodman the title of elder statesman. He is one of the very few of his generation (C. Wright Mills is another) whose experience the radical young consider relevant, whose integrity they trust, whose sympathy they value.
